In a Spring MVC application, the routing or URL mapping is typically defined in the configuration class or file. This configuration class is responsible for specifying how incoming requests are mapped to particular controller classes and methods.

Here's an example of how you can define the routing in a Spring MVC configuration:

```java
@Configuration
@EnableWebMvc
public class WebConfig implements WebMvcConfigurer {

  @Override
  public void addViewControllers(ViewControllerRegistry registry) {
    registry.addViewController("/").setViewName("index");
  }

  @Override
  public void addResourceHandlers(ResourceHandlerRegistry registry) {
    registry
      .addResourceHandler("/static/**")
      .addResourceLocations("/static/");
  }

  @Override
  public void configureDefaultServletHandling(DefaultServletHandlerConfigurer configurer) {
    configurer.enable();
  }

}
```

In the above example, we have a configuration class called WebConfig that implements the WebMvcConfigurer interface. This class can be annotated with @Configuration to indicate that it provides bean definitions and configuration settings for the application.

The @EnableWebMvc annotation is used to enable Spring MVC configuration.

Inside the WebConfig class, we can override methods provided by WebMvcConfigurer to configure various aspects of Spring MVC.

For example, the addViewControllers() method is used to map a specific URL ("/") to a view name ("index"). This is useful when you want to define simple URL mappings that just render a specific view without the need for a controller.

The addResourceHandlers() method is used to map specific resource locations (such as static files like CSS or JavaScript) to an URL pattern ("/static/**") so that they can be accessed by the client.

The configureDefaultServletHandling() method is used to enable the default servlet handling, ensuring that requests that are not handled by Spring MVC are still handled by the default servlet container.

Now, when it comes to routing requests to the ProductController, assuming you have defined the @Controller and @RequestMapping annotations as mentioned earlier, Spring MVC will use its internal mechanisms to handle the routing.

The configured routes in the WebConfig class and the annotated controllers play a crucial role in mapping incoming requests to the corresponding controller methods.

For example, with the @RequestMapping("/products") annotation on a method in the ProductController, Spring MVC will associate the URL pattern "/products" with that specific method. So, when a request is made to your application with the "/products" URL, Spring MVC will route it to the appropriate method in the ProductController for processing.

It's important to note that Spring MVC relies on reflection and the underlying servlet container's mechanisms to handle mapping and dispatching of requests. The routing and handling of requests are abstracted away from the developers, thanks to the configuration and annotations provided by Spring MVC.

In ASP.NET Core MVC, the routing configuration is typically defined in the Startup class of your application. The Startup class contains the necessary configuration code for routing, middleware, services, and other aspects of your application.

Here's an example of how routing can be configured in ASP.NET Core MVC:

```csharp
public class Startup
{
    public void ConfigureServices(IServiceCollection services)
    {
        services.AddControllersWithViews();
    }

    public void Configure(IApplicationBuilder app, IWebHostEnvironment env)
    {
        if (env.IsDevelopment())
        {
            app.UseDeveloperExceptionPage();
        }
        else
        {
            app.UseExceptionHandler("/Home/Error");
            app.UseHsts();
        }

        app.UseHttpsRedirection();
        app.UseStaticFiles();

        app.UseRouting();

        app.UseEndpoints(endpoints =>
        {
            endpoints.MapControllerRoute(
                name: "default",
                pattern: "{controller=Home}/{action=Index}/{id?}");
        });
    }
}
```

In the above example, we have the ConfigureServices method which is used to configure services needed for the application. Here, we are adding controllers and views by calling `services.AddControllersWithViews()`.

In the Configure method, we configure the middleware pipeline for handling requests. Depending on the environment (development or production), different error handling and HTTPS redirection middleware are applied.

The important part for routing is the `app.UseRouting()` method, which enables routing within the ASP.NET Core middleware pipeline.

The `app.UseEndpoints` method is responsible for mapping incoming requests to their respective controllers and actions. In this example, we are using the `MapControllerRoute` method to map the default route. The `pattern` parameter specifies the route pattern, where `{controller=Home}` specifies the default controller if not provided in the URL, `{action=Index}` specifies the default action if not provided, and `{id?}` specifies an optional parameter in the URL.

With this configuration, when a request comes in, ASP.NET Core MVC will use the routing information defined in the `UseEndpoints` method to map the requested URL to the appropriate controller and action method for processing.

The controller itself is defined as a class with methods decorated with attributes like `[Controller]`, `[HttpGet]`, `[HttpPost]`, etc. These attributes specify the HTTP verb and route pattern associated with the action method.

Note that ASP.NET Core MVC follows a convention-based approach for routing, where the URL structure is based on the controller and action names. However, you can also define custom route patterns using attributes like `[Route]` on the controller or action methods if desired.

Overall, the routing in ASP.NET Core MVC is handled through the Startup class and the configured middleware pipeline, allowing you to map incoming requests to the appropriate controllers and actions for processing.
